-- Lesson 7.1: Identifying Core Wounds (Uncovering the Hidden Blueprint)
-- 79 blocks, 30 min estimated read time
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes": 30, "blocks": [{"type": "heading", "content": "Uncovering the Hidden Blueprint: Your Subconscious Survival Code"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Let''s pause. Breathe in... breathe out... together, nice and slow. In Module 6:4, you practiced catching that exact moment when your Green Zone starts shrinking. You noticed it early, without judgment, without shaming yourself. You just listened. Do you remember what we discovered? A shrinking Green Zone isn''t a failure. It''s information."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "A shrinking Green Zone isn''t a failure. It''s information. It''s your nervous system leaning in and whispering, ''Hey... an old program just kicked on. Something familiar is driving the bus right now.''"}, {"type": "text", "content": "This module is your warm, cozy invitation to finally sit down with that program. To understand where it came from, why it''s still hanging around, and how it''s been trying to protect you and keep you safe your whole life, even when it feels like it''s holding you back. No blame lives here. Only compassion, clarity, and the sweet beginning of freedom. Honestly, this is the part where so many people let out the biggest exhale and whisper: ''Ohhh... so I''m not crazy after all. I''m just deeply patterned.''"}, {"type": "text", "content": "We''re gently lifting the veil on the invisible forces that have been quietly shaping your closest relationships, your marriage, and honestly... pretty much every corner of your beautiful life. By the end of this module, you will clearly understand:"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["The massive power difference between your conscious and subconscious mind (and why they basically speak two different languages)", "How your subconscious quietly runs the show on most of your emotional reactions before your thinking brain even wakes up", "The 12 Key Principles that govern how the subconscious operates and exactly why change can feel so stubbornly hard at first (spoiler: it''s not you)", "The key brain regions that make up your subconscious ''dream team'' and why they''re so important for healing"]}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "Meet the Giant Behind the Curtain"}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Your subconscious handles 95-97% of your brain''s processing power, millions of bits per second, while your conscious mind is stuck with just 3-5%, processing a measly 40-50 bits per second."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Pause. Let that sink in. All the working, talking, planning, adulting, goal-setting, and ''I really should know better by now'' inner pep talks you give yourself? That''s only tapping into about 5% of your total brainpower. The other 95%+? That''s your subconscious quietly running the entire operation:"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Scanning your whole environment (every micro-expression, tone shift, body language cue)", "Firing emotional reactions", "Running habits on autopilot", "Storing memories forever", "Driving your car (literally  --  thank goodness)", "Protecting you faster than you can blink"]}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your conscious mind speaks fluent language, logic, words, and reasoning. It''s the strategist, the critic, the one saying ''Next time I''ll do better.'' Your subconscious? It speaks emotion, vivid imagery, felt experiences, and repetition. It literally does not understand words the way your thinking brain does. That means it doesn''t respond to lectures."}, {"type": "text", "content": "That''s why saying ''I shouldn''t feel this way'' or ''Just stop reacting'' does... absolutely nothing. Except make you more frustrated when the reaction keeps happening anyway. The subconscious didn''t hear the sentence. It felt the fear. It saw the old picture. It filed the experience."}, {"type": "quote", "content": "The subconscious mind speaks in the language of emotion and imagery.", "attribution": "Thais Gibson"}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Conscious vs Subconscious: Who''s Really Driving?"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Conscious Mind (the logical strategist):", "Only 3-5% of processing power", "Loves words, plans, explanations, and ''next time I''ll do better''"]}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Subconscious Mind (the ancient protector):", "95-97% of processing power", "Instant emotional reactions", "Deeply ingrained habits", "Automatic thoughts and gut feelings", "Survival responses", "Threat detection", "Memory filing at lightning speed"]}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "lightbulb", "content": "The conscious mind draws the map. The subconscious steers the car  --  and slams on the brakes when it smells danger. It responds to a deep sense of safety, not clever arguments."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Why Words Bounce Off  --  And Where Healing Actually Happens"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Words and logic? That''s conscious territory. Emotion + imagery + repetition is how you speak directly to the boss. Healing happens when we speak the subconscious''s native language:"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Emotion and feelings", "Imagery and visualization", "Repetition", "Regulation", "Safe experiences", "Co-regulation with a safe person"]}, {"type": "text", "content": "This is why co-regulation, vivid visualizations that create new internal pictures, and repeated calm moments are pure gold  --  they bypass the thinking mind and go straight to the heart of change, where new patterns form and old wounds finally soften. They speak the language the Boss actually understands."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "The Pink Elephant Principle"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Quick experiment: Whatever you do... don''t think of a pink elephant. No trunk. No floppy ears, and definitely not wearing a sparkly purple tutu. NO, DON''T DO IT! ...How''d that go? Exactly. Your subconscious doesn''t process negatives like ''don''t,'' ''not,'' or ''stop.'' It hears only the vivid image: PINK ELEPHANT IN A SPARKLY PURPLE TUTU. So when we tell ourselves:"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["''Don''t shut down.''  --  Your subconscious hears: SHUT DOWN", "''Don''t get anxious.''  --  Your subconscious hears: ANXIETY", "''Don''t mess this up.''  --  Your subconscious hears: MESS UP"]}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "lightbulb", "content": "Healing Reframe: Instead of ''Don''t leave me,'' try: ''It''s safe to pause and breathe here. Connection is on its way.'' Close your eyes and imagine what that warm, steady connection feels like in your body."}, {"type": "quote", "content": "We always grow toward the light we focus on  --  not away from the shadows we fight.", "attribution": "Trisha Jamison"}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "The 12 Key Principles of the Subconscious Mind"}, {"type": "text", "content": "If you''ve ever wondered, ''I know better  --  why do I still react this way?'' or ''Why do I keep repeating the same patterns?'' This is for you. Change feels hard not because you''re resistant or failing, but because your subconscious operates by specific, protective rules. When you understand those rules, confusion turns into compassion, and compassion becomes real power."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 1  --  The Subconscious Is the Boss"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your subconscious mind governs about 95-97% of your reactions, while your conscious mind manages only 3-5%. So even when you want to change, if your subconscious perceives something as unsafe, it will override logic every time. This is biology."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 2  --  The Subconscious Learns by Repetition"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your patterns and behaviors were not created once. They were created over and over again. What''s been repeated for years doesn''t disappear after one insight. The good news? The same rule applies to healing."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 3  --  Repetition + Emotion Creates Programming"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Emotion is the glue that locks patterns in place. When strong feelings are paired with repeated experiences, deep subconscious beliefs are formed. That''s why emotionally charged moments  --  both painful and positive  --  leave such a lasting imprint. It''s also why calm, emotionally safe experiences, repeated over time, are what truly heal and rewire those patterns."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 4  --  The Subconscious Speaks the Language of Emotion and Imagery"}, {"type": "text", "content": "The subconscious doesn''t respond to logic or explanations. It understands how something feels, what it looks like, and what it reminds you of. Explanations bounce off, but felt experiences and vivid images land. You can''t reason your way into safety. You have to experience it."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 5  --  Visualization + Emotion Is the Language of Change"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Words without feeling don''t reach the subconscious. However, when emotion is paired with clear imagery, the body begins to believe something new is possible. Your brain responds to vividly imagined experiences much like real ones  --  feel it, and it becomes believable. That''s why visualization, breath, and a sense of safety are such powerful tools for change."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 6  --  Logic Does Not Reprogram Survival Responses"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Survival patterns were formed long before logic fully developed. So even when you know better, your nervous system may still react the old way. Old patterns bypass insight and move straight into action. That''s why healing must involve the emotional, body-based brain  --  not just understanding what''s happening."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 7  --  The Pink Elephant Rule"}, {"type": "text", "content": "The subconscious doesn''t understand ''don''t,'' ''not,'' or ''stop.'' It responds to images. So when you focus on what you don''t want, your brain unintentionally reinforces it. The picture gets stronger, not weaker. Change happens when you move toward safety, not away from fear."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 8  --  There Is No Off Switch"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your subconscious is always learning  --  whether you mean to or not. Tone of voice. Environment. Repeated thoughts. Everything is information. All input. Nothing is neutral."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 9  --  Beliefs Drive Patterns Across All 8 Areas of Life"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Beliefs don''t stay in one category. A belief formed in relationships affects all 8 areas of life: emotional, intellectual, physical, career, financial, spiritual, social, and environmental. That''s why change in one area often requires awareness of the whole system."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 10  --  Early Life Is a Super-Learning Period"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Most core beliefs are formed before age 8, when the brain absorbs meaning and emotions without context. These beliefs weren''t chosen. They were learned, but learned beliefs can be relearned."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 11  --  Prefers Familiarity Over Happiness"}, {"type": "text", "content": "What''s known  --  even if it''s painful  --  can feel safer than what''s new and healthy. That''s why chaos can feel more comfortable than calm, and why growth often feels uncomfortable at first."}, {"type": "quote", "content": "Your subconscious is wired for familiarity, not happiness.", "attribution": "Thais Gibson"}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Principle 12  --  The Subconscious Is a Massive Data Collector"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your subconscious processes far more information than your conscious mind ever could. It constantly scans tone, facial expressions, body sensations, emotions, and memory  --  using all of it, instantly, to decide how to protect you. Most of this happens far beyond conscious awareness."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Bonus Principle 13  --  There Is No True Self-Sabotage"}, {"type": "text", "content": "What looks like sabotage is actually protection. Your subconscious is not working against you... it''s working from an old rulebook. Healing is not about fighting yourself. It''s about updating the rules."}, {"type": "quote", "content": "Until you make the unconscious conscious, it will direct your life and you will call it fate.", "attribution": "Carl Jung"}, {"type": "text", "content": "These principles aren''t overwhelming, they''re liberating. Knowledge turns mystery into a roadmap for success. It will help you get where you want to go."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Where Does the Subconscious Live in the Brain?"}, {"type": "text", "content": "There''s no single ''subconscious headquarters.'' It''s a beautiful symphony of brain systems working together behind the scenes to keep life running smoothly."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Basal Ganglia  --  autopilot habits", "Amygdala (critter brain)  --  emotional smoke alarm (floods first, thinks later)", "Hippocampus  --  emotional memory archivist (files everything)", "Cerebellum  --  lightning-fast body reflexes", "Brainstem and Limbic System  --  primal survival + attachment needs"]}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Why the Subconscious Runs the Show in Relationships"}, {"type": "text", "content": "You feel before you think. Instant scan: Am I safe? Will I be abandoned? Am I being controlled? Have I felt this before? Reactions are automatic because protection is faster than conscious thought. This is neural survival brilliance."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "Real, lasting transformation happens when we speak the subconscious''s language: vivid imagery and visualization, repetition of new safe experiences, emotional co-regulation, and building a deep sense of safety  --  that warm, internal ''I''m okay here'' feeling."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "A Note From Trisha"}, {"type": "text", "content": "If you''re feeling a little overwhelmed right now, that''s okay. This is big, meaningful work  --  seeing how much of your life has been shaped by ancient, protective programs that you didn''t consciously choose. That realization alone can feel overwhelming. Here''s the beautiful truth: Awareness is the first step to freedom. You are human, brilliantly wired for survival... and now for healing. Take a breath. You''ve already done the hard part by showing up and staying curious."}, {"type": "text", "content": "This week, when you notice the urge to change something within yourself, shift your focus away from words and logic and toward visualization, imagery, and emotion. Let yourself see safety, feel steadiness, imagine connection. That''s the language your subconscious understands, and it''s where real change begins."}, {"type": "exercise", "title": "Reflection 1: Subconscious Awareness", "prompt": "Think of a recent moment where your body reacted strongly  --  a tight chest, a sudden silence, a wave of frustration or sadness.", "steps": ["Now gently ask yourself: What might this remind my subconscious of from the past? A childhood moment? A repeated experience? A familiar relational pattern?", "No digging. No judging. Just noticing with kindness."]}, {"type": "exercise", "title": "Reflection 2: The 12 Principles Check-In", "prompt": "Look back over the 12 Principles. Which one stood out to you most? Why do you think it caught your attention?", "steps": ["Reflect softly: Can you spot this principle playing out somewhere in your life right now?", "This might be in relationships, routines, self-talk, work, or stress responses.", "Awareness alone is powerful."]}, {"type": "exercise", "title": "Reflection 3: Reframe Playtime", "prompt": "Write down a familiar negative thought or self-talk phrase. Now gently rewrite it  --  not with forced positivity, but by moving toward what you want instead of away from what you fear.", "steps": ["Pause for a moment. If it feels okay, close your eyes.", "Say the new phrase quietly or out loud.", "Imagine it with feeling  --  what does safety or steadiness look like here?", "What do you notice in your body? More breath? Less tension? A softening? No change yet? That''s okay too.", "Even the smallest shift counts."]}, {"type": "exercise", "title": "Reflection 4: Daily Noticing Practice", "prompt": "Over the next week, notice one moment each day where you feel before you think.", "steps": ["When it happens, gently ask: What triggered the quick scan? What might my subconscious have been trying to protect me from?", "You don''t need to change anything yet. This is about witnessing, not fixing.", "Jot down any observations you''d like.", "And don''t skip this part: Celebrate the awareness. Catching it is the work right now."]}, {"type": "quote", "content": "You are learning a new language  --  the language of your nervous system. That takes patience. It takes compassion. You are already doing it beautifully.", "attribution": "Trisha Jamison"}]}'
WHERE module_id = (SELECT id FROM modules WHERE module_number = '7') AND sort_order = 1;

-- Lesson 7.2: The Power of Forgiveness
-- 67 blocks, 30 min estimated read time
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes": 30, "blocks": [{"type": "heading", "content": "The Power of Forgiveness: Releasing the Chains That Bind"}, {"type": "text", "content": "We''ve powered through 7 modules now  --  that''s a serious commitment to transformation. If your brain feels like it''s been through an emotional boot camp (complete with subconscious push-ups), pat yourself on the back. This isn''t lightweight stuff."}, {"type": "text", "content": "In Module 7:1, we unlocked the 12 Key Principles of the Subconscious Brain. We saw how your mind isn''t just a recorder  --  it''s a relentless architect, building patterns from emotional imprints, habitual loops, and protective barriers. Those principles showed us that resentment isn''t just \"bad vibes.\" It''s a subconscious glitch that keeps you stuck in survival mode."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Module 7:2 isn''t here to pile on more theory. It''s your invitation to RELEASE. We''re tying those principles directly into forgiveness as the ultimate reset: A sacred, Christ-centered process that honors your pain, reprograms your subconscious, and frees your heart."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Forgiveness is about telling your own body, with clarity and authority: This no longer gets to run me."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Why unforgiveness keeps your subconscious locked in protection mode", "How resentment quietly shrinks your Green Zone", "The clear difference between forgiveness, trust, and reconciliation", "Why emotional release should never require unsafe connection", "How to forgive without minimizing pain or abandoning boundaries", "The physical, emotional, and spiritual cost of holding onto bitterness"]}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "From Awareness to Release"}, {"type": "text", "content": "In Module 7:1, you learned something that changes everything once you truly let it sink in: Your subconscious is not random. Your reactions are not personal flaws. Your patterns were created to protect you."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Here is the piece most people never learn:"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "lightbulb", "content": "Insight helps you understand the pattern, but forgiveness is what releases the emotional charge that keeps the pattern alive."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your subconscious does not store experiences as \"over and done with.\" It stores them as felt experiences  --  unfinished emotional loops that remain active until the body receives enough safety to let them go. As long as those loops remain open, your nervous system stays on alert  --  scanning, bracing, protecting, and reacting as if the past is still happening now."}, {"type": "text", "content": "In relationships, forgiveness becomes the game-changer that turns relational mirroring from pain-echoing to love-amplifying."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Forgiveness has often been taught in rushed or emotionally unsafe ways  --  framed as something you have to do rather than something your heart, your nervous system, and the healing presence of Christ are invited into when they are ready."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Resistant to Forgive"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Many people resist forgiveness because they have been taught a version of it that feels unjust or dangerous."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Saying \"It didn''t matter\" when it absolutely did", "Allowing harmful behavior to continue", "Skipping accountability", "Rebuilding trust overnight", "Forgetting what happened"]}, {"type": "quote", "content": "Let all bitterness, and wrath, and anger, and clamour, and evil speaking, be put away from you, with all malice: And be ye kind one to another, tenderhearted, forgiving one another, even as God for Christ''s sake hath forgiven you.", "attribution": "Ephesians 4:31-32"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Notice that it does not say to deny the hurt  --  only to stop letting it rule the heart."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "If forgiveness required self-betrayal, your nervous system would be right to resist it."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "What Forgiveness Actually Is: A Subconscious Skill"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Everything you learned in Module 7:1 applies directly here. The subconscious learns through emotion and repetition, not through logic or lectures. It stores pain as felt experience, not as rational narrative."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Chronic muscle tension", "Emotional reactivity or shutdown", "Hypervigilance and anxiety", "Relational distance and guardedness"]}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Forgiveness does not erase a memory. It releases the emotional charge attached to the memory, and when that charge releases, the body can finally exhale."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Why the Body Holds On When the Heart Is Hurt"}, {"type": "text", "content": "As trauma researcher Bessel van der Kolk explains: When hurt is not processed, it does not disappear  --  it relocates. Pain settles into the nervous system, muscles, breath, gut, and heart. Over time, this stored pain begins to shape how we live, how we love, and how we protect ourselves."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Holding onto anger is like drinking poison and expecting the other person to suffer. The body always pays the price."}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Physical Impact"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Muscle tension, especially in the shoulders and neck", "Jaw clenching or teeth grinding", "Headaches or migraines", "Shallow or restricted breathing", "Digestive issues", "Ongoing fatigue", "Anxiety or restlessness", "A constant feeling of being \"on edge\""]}, {"type": "text", "content": "Sleep becomes lighter and more disrupted. Stress hormones remain elevated. Over time, the immune system can become suppressed, leaving the body more vulnerable to illness, inflammation, and slower healing."}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Emotional Impact"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Heightened anxiety or irritability", "Emotional shutdown or numbness", "Overreactions to small triggers", "Withdrawal from closeness or connection", "A shrinking Green Zone"]}, {"type": "text", "content": "Many describe this as carrying an emotional backpack filled with rocks  --  joy feels heavier, trust feels riskier, and intimacy requires far more effort than it should."}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Spiritual Impact"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["A sense of distance from peace or God''s presence", "Prayer feeling flat or mechanical", "Spiritual growth feeling stalled", "A guarded heart that struggles to receive patience and grace"]}, {"type": "text", "content": "This is not spiritual failure. It is a nervous system that learns protection before trust."}, {"type": "text", "content": "When anger is healthy and contained, it can be an essential part of healing. It helps the nervous system recognize that a boundary was crossed and that something mattered deeply. Bitterness develops when anger is sustained without repair  --  leading to chronic stress, emotional rigidity, and long-term physical health consequences."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "Stories of Forgiveness"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Sarah: When Betrayal Lives in the Body"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Sarah was forty-two, a busy mom of two, when she discovered her husband''s emotional affair. She later said her body reacted before her mind could catch up. From that moment on, her body stayed on guard. The bitterness didn''t just live in her thoughts  --  it settled into her body. Chronic tension formed in her neck and shoulders. Migraines began waking her up at three in the morning. Her nervous system chose vigilance over rest. Every innocent text triggered suspicion. Her mind replayed unanswered questions on a loop. Emotion paired with repetition strengthened the pattern. Her Green Zone shrank so much that even a hug felt risky."}, {"type": "text", "content": "One night, she read words she had heard before, but this time they landed differently. She began in prayer, to visualize the burden she had been carrying  --  a heavy backpack filled with fear, anger, and grief  --  and placed it in Christ''s hands. Night after night, she let Him take it. Safe imagery paired with emotion allowed her body to release what words never could. Over time, the migraines eased, and she felt lighter. Their marriage healed very slowly through honesty and accountability. Forgiveness didn''t erase the story  --  it changed how the story lived inside her."}, {"type": "quote", "content": "Come unto me, all ye that labour and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest.", "attribution": "Matthew 11:28"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "John: When Family Wounds Shape Marriage"}, {"type": "text", "content": "John was thirty-five and outwardly confident: reliable at work, committed to his marriage, faithful in the visible ways. Beneath that confidence lived the quiet weight of a childhood marked by emotional absence. His father wasn''t abusive  --  he was simply unavailable. John''s nervous system learned a silent rule: connection isn''t dependable. That belief didn''t stay in childhood  --  it followed him into his body and into his marriage. Under stress, ulcers flared. Doctors treated symptoms, but they kept returning. He found himself constantly scanning his wife''s tone, moods, and pauses  --  watching for signs she might pull away too."}, {"type": "text", "content": "While reading the parable of the Prodigal Son, John was struck by the father who ran  --  open arms, no lecture, no distance. For the first time, John allowed himself to feel the grief of what he never received. He wrote a raw, unsent letter to his father. Then he brought it to Christ in prayer, placing every unmet need into Christ''s hands. Finally, he burned the letter, watching the ashes as he imagined Christ carrying what he no longer needed to hold. Over time, with medical care and less internal bracing, the ulcers healed. Something new emerged  --  he stayed present instead of withdrawing, and vulnerability replaced walls."}, {"type": "quote", "content": "That bitterness was like dragging a suitcase full of bricks. Forgiveness was realizing I could finally set it down.", "attribution": "John"}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "Moving Forward with Self-Forgiveness"}, {"type": "text", "content": "For many people, the heaviest burden isn''t what someone else did to them  --  it''s what they did themselves. The words they said, the choices they made, or the moments they believed they should have known sooner, stopped earlier, spoken or handled things differently."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Why did I say that?", "Why did I act that way?", "I completely screwed this up.", "I failed.", "This is all my fault.", "Why did I stay?", "Why didn''t I speak up more?"]}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "I wasn''t holding myself accountable  --  I was holding myself hostage."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Self-forgiveness is not letting yourself off the hook or avoiding accountability. It is releasing the false belief that pain must continue in order to make up for the mistake."}, {"type": "text", "content": "It sounds like: \"I did the best I could with the safety and awareness I had then.\" And \"I can take responsibility without continuing to suffer.\" And \"Learning does not require lifelong shame.\""}, {"type": "exercise", "title": "Grounded Steps Toward Self-Forgiveness", "prompt": "Here are a few ways to move self-forgiveness from an idea into something your body can actually feel:", "steps": ["Name what you are still carrying  --  without attacking yourself. Instead of asking \"What''s wrong with me?\" gently ask \"What am I still holding onto?\" The nervous system softens when truth is spoken without judgment.", "Separate accountability from punishment. Accountability says \"I see what happened and I am willing to accept my part.\" Punishment says \"I must keep hurting to make myself stronger.\" Those are not the same thing, and your body knows the difference.", "Offer yourself the compassion you would give someone you love. If your child, spouse, or closest friend made the same mistake, would you demand lifelong shame  --  or would you hope they learn, grow, and move forward?", "Release the belief that suffering is required for growth. Growth can come from reflection, repair, and responsibility  --  not ongoing self-attack."]}, {"type": "quote", "content": "However late you think you are, however many chances you think you have missed... you have not traveled beyond the reach of divine love.", "attribution": "Elder Jeffrey R. Holland"}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "A Note From Trisha"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Christ comes first. Always. Forgiveness does not begin with effort or willpower  --  it begins with His presence. Christ does not ask you to release pain on your own. He steps into the places where the weight lives and says, \"Let me carry this with you.\""}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your subconscious exists to protect you. It remembers what hurt and holds it as sensation and survival, not as logic. That''s why understanding alone is never enough. The subconscious releases only when it finally feels safe. When forgiveness is anchored in Christ, safety arrives at a level words cannot reach. The nervous system stands down. Old loops soften. The body exhales."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "Forgiveness stops being a moral task and becomes restoration  --  biological, emotional, and spiritual."}, {"type": "exercise", "title": "Individual Reflection", "prompt": "Take your time with these. Journal. Sit quietly. Pray if that feels right. Let your body lead just as much as your mind.", "steps": ["What hurt or resentment did I notice living most strongly in my body during this module?", "Where do I feel it physically  --  tension, fatigue, breath, gut, chest?", "What fear arises when I imagine fully releasing it?", "What feels safe to release now  --  even if I''m not ready to release everything?", "What boundaries do I still need in place as I continue healing?"]}, {"type": "exercise", "title": "Optional Couple Conversation", "prompt": "Share only what feels appropriate.", "steps": ["One thing my body has been holding onto is...", "One way forgiveness is changing how I show up is...", "What helps me feel safer as I continue healing is..."]}, {"type": "quote", "content": "Bitterness doesn''t protect the heart. It keeps the wound open.", "attribution": "Trisha Jamison"}]}'
WHERE module_id = (SELECT id FROM modules WHERE module_number = '7') AND sort_order = 2;

-- Lesson 7.3: From Letting Go to Living Free
-- ~120 blocks, 40 min estimated read time
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes": 40, "blocks": [{"type": "heading", "content": "Module 7:3 -- From Letting Go to Living Free"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Healing at the Root: Introduction"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Module 7 has guided an inward journey: uncovering subconscious survival codes in 7:1, releasing burdens and fostering forgiveness in 7:2, and now shifting to living free in 7:3."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "In this module, you''ll explore:"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["How stress or pain-formed beliefs wired into your nervous system.", "The BTEA cycle that perpetuates old patterns.", "Transforming painful emotions into reliable feedback.", "Two practical tools for lasting bodily change.", "Rewiring through safety, compassion, skill, and faith."]}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Why Patterns Persist"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Despite efforts like prayer and forgiveness, the nervous system retains old ''software'' from unsafe moments, triggering anxiety, shutdowns, or reflexes. Beliefs like ''I''m not safe'' or ''I must stay guarded'' were survival adaptations."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Forgiveness alters meaning; reprogramming shifts conditioning. Jesus offers grace, but healing involves participation, new learning, safety, and repetition to embody truth."}, {"type": "text", "content": "This module builds on the Healing Hearts Renewal Framework: awareness -> release -> renewal, blending familiar and new concepts with slow, repetitive practice for deep absorption."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Understanding the BTEA Cycle: Beliefs -> Thoughts -> Emotions -> Actions"}, {"type": "text", "content": "This invisible loop powers most of what we do. We rarely see it running  --  we just feel the emotion and react. Once you understand it, you get to step in and take the wheel."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["You carry core beliefs (many formed before age 7, shaped by your early attachment style: secure, anxious, avoidant, or disorganized).", "Those beliefs spark automatic thoughts, often slipping in without you noticing.", "Thoughts trigger real neurochemical emotions.", "Your Reticular Activating System (RAS) acts as the brain''s loyal filter, quietly scanning for evidence that matches those core beliefs.", "Emotions fuel your actions  --  even the ones you wish you could take back."]}, {"type": "text", "content": "Let''s pause here for a moment on those core beliefs, because they''re often shaped by our earliest attachment experiences."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "The 4 Attachment Styles"}, {"type": "text", "content": "We''ve talked about these in a previous module, but here''s a quick overview with real-life examples in adult relationships:"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "lightbulb", "content": "Secure Attachment (the oak tree  --  strong roots, flexible branches): Comfortable with intimacy and independence. Trusts others, communicates openly, handles conflict calmly, and believes they are worthy of love. Seeks support naturally and gives space without fear."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Example: Sarah calls her partner after a hard day and leaves a voicemail: ''Rough one! I could use a hug tonight.'' No panic if the reply is delayed  --  she knows she''s safe."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "Anxious Attachment (the octopus  --  reaching for reassurance): Craves closeness but fears abandonment. Negative self-view, positive view of others. Seeks constant validation, gets jealous or clingy during uncertainty."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Example: Mia hears her partner mention an old friend and spirals: ''They must prefer someone more exciting.'' She probes with questions or fishes for compliments, even though it was harmless."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "alert", "content": "Avoidant Attachment (the turtle in its shell  --  safe inside, but hard to reach): Prioritizes independence, pulls back from vulnerability. Positive self-view, doubts others'' reliability. Avoids deep emotions, values self-reliance."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Example: Jordan''s partner wants to discuss feelings after a fight. Jordan deflects: ''It''s fine  --  let''s move on.'' He enjoys the relationship but resists deeper commitment to stay ''free.''"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "alert", "content": "Disorganized Attachment (the cat in a tree  --  wants down, but is terrified): Craves connection but fears it. Mixes anxious and avoidant traits from chaotic or frightening early experiences. Swings between pursuing intensely and withdrawing suddenly."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Example: Taylor longs for intimacy but panics when it gets close. They chase hard one week, then sabotage or disappear the next."}, {"type": "text", "content": "These styles aren''t fixed labels  --  they''re early patterns that can shift toward secure and safe relationships with consistent practice (like the tools we''re using here). Most people lean toward one, but show traits of others in different situations."}, {"type": "text", "content": "If one attachment pattern feels familiar, that''s powerful insight, not judgment. It''s simply a doorway to healing. You''re already stepping through it by noticing and gently questioning those old imprints."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Because these core beliefs and attachment patterns are so foundational, they don''t just stay in the mind  --  they create very real physical responses in the body."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Neurochemical Emotions"}, {"type": "text", "content": "When we say emotions are neurochemical reactions, we mean they''re not just feelings in your head  --  they''re physical events in your body and brain. Every emotion triggers a cascade of chemicals:"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Fear or anxiety floods you with adrenaline and cortisol (fight/flight).", "Sadness or grief lowers serotonin and dopamine while increasing stress hormones.", "Joy or connection releases oxytocin, endorphins, and dopamine  --  the feel-good chemicals that make you feel safe and bonded."]}, {"type": "text", "content": "These chemicals change your heart rate, breathing, muscle tension, even digestion. That''s why a triggered belief can make your chest tighten, your stomach drop, or your whole body freeze. Your nervous system is literally responding as if the old danger is happening right now."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "Reprogramming can shift those chemical responses so calm, safety, and peace become the new default."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "The Reticular Activating System (RAS)"}, {"type": "text", "content": "The RAS functions like a filter in the brain. It helps determine what you notice, what stands out, and what your mind automatically pays attention to. When you''ve carried limiting beliefs or core wounds for a long time, your RAS has been quietly scanning for evidence that confirms those beliefs  --  not because you are broken or negative, but because your nervous system learned certain stories about what keeps you safe."}, {"type": "text", "content": "You may find yourself more quickly noticing rejection, disappointment, or moments of feeling unseen or not enough. This does not mean those experiences define your life. It simply means your system has been trained to look for them."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Here is the hopeful part. The RAS is not fixed."}, {"type": "text", "content": "As you begin gently updating your beliefs, your brain also begins learning to look for different kinds of evidence. You start to notice moments of safety. You see small efforts, subtle repairs, and tiny signs of growth. You become more aware of kindness, care, and connection that may have been there all along, but your RAS was focusing on something else."}, {"type": "text", "content": "As you invite Christ into this process, He does not bypass your brain  --  He helps restore it, guiding you toward truth instead of fear. Life does not suddenly become perfect, but your system is no longer only scanning for danger."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your brain is simply being retrained through experience. As your beliefs shift and your RAS begins to notice safety instead of threat, those old emotional signals that once felt overwhelming become easier to hear as allies rather than enemies. This is the power of new learning, safety, and repetition  --  slowly turning what used to feel like chaos into clear, compassionate feedback."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Why Negative Emotions Are Actually Your Best Friends"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Emotions are never the enemy. They''re messengers. They''re the smoke alarm telling you a belief is triggered or a need is unmet. Here is the order that sets you free:"}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "1. Feel the emotion (don''t shame it)"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Pause and allow it to be there fully. Name it, breathe into it, and notice where it lives in your body. There''s no need to rush or judge. This act of allowing creates a sense of safety and often softens the intensity."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "2. Question the thought or belief behind it"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Ask gently: ''Is this 100% true? What evidence supports or challenges this story? What would I say to a loved one who believed this?'' This step helps interrupt the automatic loop."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "3. Identify the unmet need"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Ask: ''What do I really need right now  --  reassurance, rest, connection, boundaries, or self-kindness?'' Naming the need turns raw pain into a clear, actionable direction. Emotions are always valid. The beliefs or stories fueling them, however, are often outdated or untrue."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "quote", "content": "If we don''t own our beliefs and thoughts, we''re not truly in charge of our emotions or choices. Your feelings reveal your internal programming far more than they describe what''s actually happening outside.", "attribution": "Trisha Jamison"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "An Example That Might Feel Familiar"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Imagine you send a text to a close friend and they don''t reply for a few hours. Old programming from childhood experiences of feeling ignored or abandoned kicks in: ''People who love me always leave or forget me.''"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Attachment style: Anxious. This is a deep fear of abandonment that comes from inconsistent early caregiving, where love felt unreliable and you learned to stay vigilant to keep it from disappearing. What your body feels: Sudden tightness in the chest, racing thoughts  --  ''They must be mad at me,'' ''I''m too much,'' ''I''m not worth responding to''  --  and a wave of anxiety or sadness as neurochemicals are released."}, {"type": "text", "content": "What actually happened outside: Your friend is in a meeting, driving, or just busy. They''re not upset with you at all."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "lightbulb", "content": "Your emotions are honest  --  they''re just reading from an old script. When that script gets triggered, it feels 100% true in the moment, but it''s often replaying yesterday''s story, not today''s facts."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Instead of spiraling into resentment or sending a passive-aggressive follow-up, you pause and use the tool:"}, {"type": "list", "ordered": true, "items": ["Feel the anxiety. Name it: ''My heart is racing. I feel small and scared.''", "Question the belief. Ask yourself: ''Is it 100% true that they are abandoning me? What evidence shows this isn''t true?'' Find three pieces of evidence that challenge the belief.", "Identify the unmet need: ''I need reassurance, connection, and to feel seen right now.'' Then meet it healthily  --  text a different supportive person, self-soothe with a grounding breath, remind yourself: ''I''m safe. Delays don''t equal danger.''"]}, {"type": "text", "content": "Over time, as you keep practicing, the pattern shifts. Your nervous system begins to learn a new truth: ''A delayed text isn''t dangerous. I can feel secure even when someone''s busy.'' The anxiety softens, the shutdown eases, the people-pleasing quiets down, and you start responding from calm instead of fear."}, {"type": "text", "content": "You are safe to feel everything. Those big feelings don''t scare away love  --  they invite deeper healing."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Your Brain Is a Needs-Meeting Machine"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Your brain is a brilliant needs-meeting machine. The problem is, it will always choose the fastest path to feel safe and secure  --  not necessarily the wisest or healthiest one  --  until you give it better, more effective options, especially when those options follow your values."}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Reprogramming Your Brain: The First Steps"}, {"type": "text", "content": "There are many steps to truly reprogramming your brain and nervous system so the old survival code can finally rest. We''re not rushing through them all in this module  --  we''ll move slowly and intentionally. Right now, we''re focusing on the foundational first two steps. These two exercises are powerful on their own, and they build the safety and awareness your system needs before we layer in more advanced practices later."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "Exercise 1: What Beliefs Shape My Life?"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Purpose: To bring conscious awareness to the limiting beliefs quietly running each area of your life, so you can plant new, intentional seeds of what''s possible."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Why we start here: Before we question and rewire in the heat of a trigger, it helps to first see the bigger picture  --  where are the old stories living? This exercise shines a soft light on them without diving deeper quite yet. It''s like mapping the territory before we start the journey."}, {"type": "text", "content": "A gentle note on roots: Many of these limiting beliefs were shaped early in life through your attachment style. If you notice patterns like fear of abandonment in relationships, difficulty trusting support, or pulling away emotionally  --  that''s valuable insight, not judgment. It simply points to where your system learned to protect itself."}, {"type": "exercise", "title": "Exercise 1: What Beliefs Shape My Life?", "prompt": "For each area of your life, write one clear, hopeful sentence describing the outcome you truly desire  --  as if anything were possible and success were guaranteed.", "steps": ["Ask yourself: ''What would I want to create if I knew I was safe, supported, and loved, no matter what?''", "Keep your statements simple and positive, using present or near-future tense.", "If you get stuck, start with ''I am free to...'' or ask ''What would I want to create if I truly believed I was safe and supported?''"]}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "lightbulb", "content": "Quick Tip: If you get stuck, start with ''I am free to...'' Write it. Own it. You''re allowed to want good things."}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "Exercise 2: The Emotional Processing Tool"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Purpose: To interrupt emotional spirals in real time by slowing down, identifying what you''re feeling, uncovering the story underneath it, and choosing a healthier response. This is your everyday reprogramming tool  --  the one you''ll reach for whenever you feel triggered, reactive, withdrawn, anxious, or overwhelmed. Practice this on one or two real moments per week."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Step 1: Name the Emotion"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Before we do anything else, let''s meet your body where it is. Your emotions are the language of your nervous system. Naming them is the first act of safety and compassion. Ask yourself: What am I feeling right now?"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Angry", "Anxious", "Overwhelmed", "Frustrated", "Defensive", "Resentful", "Hurt", "Sad", "Lonely", "Rejected", "Ashamed", "Insecure", "Powerless", "Unseen", "Unsafe"]}, {"type": "text", "content": "If you''re unsure, place a hand on your heart or belly and notice: Tense or tight? (Often anger or defensiveness.) Heavy or collapsed? (Often sadness or shame.) Restless or shaky? (Often anxiety.)"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Take 3 slow breaths here. Imagine a soft, warm light surrounding the feeling, like a gentle hug from the inside. No need to change it  --  just let it know you''re here and listening."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "book", "content": "Naming the emotion helps calm your nervous system and creates a small pocket of safety. Your body hears: ''I see you. You don''t have to carry this alone.''"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "book", "content": "My emotion(s):"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "lightbulb", "content": "Quick note on visualization: We''ll work more intentionally with visualization and imagery in a later module -- it''s a powerful way to speak directly to the subconscious through felt sense and gentle pictures. For now, even this small moment of imagining warmth around the emotion is already helping your body feel seen and held."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Step 2: Identify the Trigger"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Now that you''ve named the feeling and given it a moment of safety, let''s gently look at what sparked it. Ask: What just happened? Be specific -- describe the moment, not the entire history. (Example: ''My spouse interrupted me during dinner.'')"}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Common Triggers (for reference if needed)"}, {"type": "text", "content": "These are everyday moments that often light up old beliefs and send emotions surging. They don''t mean you''re broken; they mean your system is loyal and protecting you the way it learned to."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Someone doesn''t respond quickly (or at all).", "Criticism, feedback, or neutral comments that feel like judgment.", "Feeling ignored, overlooked, or interrupted.", "Conflict, arguments, or raised voices.", "Silence or withdrawal from someone close.", "Being interrupted, dismissed, or talked over.", "Success or praise for others (stirs comparison or ''not me'').", "Asking for help and getting a ''no'' or delay.", "Physical closeness or intimacy that feels vulnerable.", "Changes in routine, plans, or certainty.", "Feeling controlled, micromanaged, or not trusted.", "Being compared to others (even subtly).", "Moments of failure, mistake, or embarrassment.", "Someone else''s anger or disappointment directed at you.", "Feeling ''too much'' or ''not enough'' in a social setting."]}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "book", "content": "My trigger:"}, {"type": "text", "content": "When something like this happens and the emotion surges, pause and notice: ''What old belief just got touched?'' That single awareness is already healing. You don''t have to fix everything -- just name what''s present."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Step 3: Uncover the Meaning"}, {"type": "text", "content": "This is the heart of the process -- where the real story often reveals itself. Ask yourself: What did I make this mean about me, my worth, my relationships, my future, or how I love?"}, {"type": "text", "content": "This is not what happened. It''s what you decided it meant. Examples: ''I don''t matter.'' ''I''m not respected.'' ''I''ll always be rejected.'' ''I''m not enough.''"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "book", "content": "My painful meaning:"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Be honest. Keep it simple. This is where the old programming shows up most clearly."}, {"type": "subheading", "content": "Common Limiting Beliefs / Core Imprints (for reference)"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Use this list if you need help naming what came up. These are quiet stories that feel like truth until we shine light on them."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["I am not enough.", "I am abandoned.", "I am alone.", "I am unloved.", "I am bad.", "I am weak.", "I am unsafe.", "I am stupid.", "I am unworthy.", "I am helpless.", "I am unseen.", "I am unimportant.", "I''m defective.", "I don''t belong.", "I am misunderstood.", "I am disconnected.", "I am excluded.", "I am disrespected.", "I am rejected.", "I am trapped / stuck.", "I am powerless / have no control."]}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "These aren''t who you are. They are old survival stories your nervous system wrote to make sense of pain."}, {"type": "text", "content": "They are not facts! They are echoes from the past, and they are safe to question here."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Once you''ve written your painful meaning, ask yourself: ''Does this match any of the common limiting beliefs above?'' If yes, circle or note it. If not, write your own version. This helps you see how the belief is part of a larger pattern, and it makes it easier to challenge later."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Step 4: Question the Story"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Now gently challenge it. Ask: Can I know with 100% certainty this belief is true?"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "book", "content": "My answer:"}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Step 5: Challenge and Update"}, {"type": "text", "content": "List three pieces of evidence that do not support the painful belief that it is true."}, {"type": "list", "ordered": true, "items": ["_____", "_____", "_____"]}, {"type": "text", "content": "Is there a kinder, more balanced explanation that could also be true?"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "book", "content": "Updated belief:"}, {"type": "text", "content": "This is not about forced positivity. It is about flexibility, opening the door to new possibilities."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Step 6: Name the Need"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Under every painful reaction is an unmet need. Ask: What do I actually need right now?"}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Reassurance", "Rest", "Connection", "Boundaries", "Validation", "Space", "Self-compassion"]}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "book", "content": "My need:"}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Step 7: Choose a Healthy Strategy"}, {"type": "text", "content": "What is one small, realistic way I can meet this need? Keep it simple and doable -- no grand gestures needed."}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "book", "content": "My strategy:"}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "callout", "icon": "heart", "content": "You do not have to do this perfectly. You are learning  --  and that matters."}, {"type": "text", "content": "The goal is not to eliminate emotion. Emotion is not the enemy. The goal is to understand it, meet it with kindness, and choose a new response when needed."}, {"type": "bold_text", "content": "Emotion -> Meaning -> Belief -> Need -> New Choice"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Every time you walk through this process, you weaken an old neural pathway and strengthen a new one. This is how your brain changes."}, {"type": "quote", "content": "Forgiveness released the burden. This practice teaches your body how to live like it''s free. That is how freedom becomes practical: one steady, honest choice at a time.", "attribution": "Trisha Jamison"}, {"type": "divider"}, {"type": "heading", "content": "A Note From Trisha"}, {"type": "text", "content": "Now that you have reached the end of this module, pause for a moment and recognize what you just did. You did not simply learn information. You integrated awareness, forgiveness, and intentional change into one powerful practice. In 7:1, you saw your patterns clearly. In 7:2, you released what was heavy. In 7:3, you learned how to update what your body learned when it was trying to survive."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Christ is still the Healer. The tools you practiced are not separate from Him. He designed the mind. He understands the body. When you practice this work, you are cooperating with healing that has already begun."}, {"type": "text", "content": "Old reactions may resurface at times. That does not erase your progress. It simply means you are human. Return to what you have learned. Slow down. Practice again. Strengthen the new pathway. Then do it again. And again."}, {"type": "quote", "content": "You are no longer operating on autopilot. You are living with awareness, and that changes everything.", "attribution": "Trisha Jamison"}]}'
WHERE module_id = (SELECT id FROM modules WHERE module_number = '7') AND sort_order = 3;

-- Verify
SELECT m.title as module, m.is_preview as module_preview,
       l.title as lesson, l.sort_order, l.is_preview as lesson_preview,
       length(l.content_json::text) as content_length,
       (l.content_json::json->'estimated_minutes')::text as est_minutes,
       json_array_length(l.content_json::json->'blocks') as block_count
FROM modules m
JOIN lessons l ON l.module_id = m.id
WHERE m.module_number = '7'
ORDER BY l.sort_order;